text:
Mushroom Risotto üçÑüçö from Delicious in Dungeon üë®‚Äçüç≥üç≥

Recipe:
-100g arborio rice¬†
-3 medium sized mushrooms (e.g., shiitake or oyster), chopped
-60ml white wine
-2-3 cloves garlic, minced
-1 tablespoon unsalted butter
-400-500ml water or stock
-optional: 0.1-0.2g saffron
-1/4 teaspoon salt
-20 grated swiss cheese
-60g grated cheddar cheese
-additional salt to taste

Instructions:
In a pot, bring the water or stock to a simmer and maintain over low heat. In a separate pan, melt the butter over medium heat. Add the minced garlic and saut√© until fragrant.¬†

Add the chopped mushrooms to the pan and cook until they release their moisture and become tender. Add the rice to the pan, stirring continuously for about 2 minutes to lightly toast the grains.

Pour in the cooking wine, stirring until it's mostly absorbed by the rice. Dissolve the saffron in the broth or water. Add a ladleful of the warm stock or water to the rice, stirring frequently. Once absorbed, add another ladleful. Continue this process until the rice is al dente and has creamy consistency. This should take about 18‚Äì20 minutes.¬†

Stir in the Swiss and cheddar cheeses until melted and well combined. Taste and adjust seasoning with additional salt if necessary.¬†

Plate the risotto immediately, garnishing with extra cheese or fresh herbs if desired.

Three Layer Tea Latte üçµ from Dr. Stone

Recipe:
-30ml whipped matcha
-30ml milk
-20ml hojicha tea
-2 tbsp gum syrup

To keep the milk separate from the tea, the tea needs to have a higher density than the milk. This requires a significant amount of sugar syrup.

At least 20‚Äì30% of the total liquid should be sugar syrup.

The thicker (more concentrated) the sugar syrup, the better it will work. Pour the milk very slowly to maintain a clear separation. Cold milk on warm, dense tea enhances the layering effect.

Spaghetti and Meatballs üçù from Lady and the Tramp üë®‚Äçüç≥üêï‚ô•Ô∏è

Recipe:
-110g ground beef
-110g ground pork
-30g breadcrumbs
-15g grated Parmesan
-1 egg
-1 cloves garlic, minced
-1 tbsp chopped fresh parsley
-1/2 tsp salt¬†
-1/2 black pepper
-1/2 tsp dried oregano
-1-2 tbsp milk
-2 tbsp olive oil (for frying)

Sauce:
-1 tbsp olive oil
-1 small onion, finely chopped
-2 cloves garlic, minced
-400g canned crushed tomatoes
-200g canned tomato sauce
-1/2 tsp dried basil
-1/2 tsp dried oregano
-1/2 salt
-1/2 tsp black pepper
-1/2 tsp sugar (optional)
-1/4 cup fresh basil, chopped (optional)

Pasta:
-180g spaghetti¬†
-salt for boiling water

Instructions:
Mix all meatball ingredients in a bowl. Form 2.5 cm balls. Heat olive oil in a pan and brown meatballs on all sides. Set aside.

In the same pan, saut√© onion until soft, then add garlic. Pour in tomatoes and tomato sauce, then season with herbs, salt, pepper, and sugar. Simmer for 20-25 minutes, adding meatballs back in after 5 minutes.

Boil salted water and cook spaghetti until al dente. Drain.

Toss spaghetti with a little sauce. Plate, top with meatballs and more sauce. Garnish with Parmesan and fresh basil.¬†

text:
The EASIEST bread üçû 

I love me some good, crusty bread and I promise you: this is 100% foolproof! ü´∂
RECIPE (1 loaf, 6h prep time):
-350ml roomtemp water
-8g fresh yeast or 3g instant yeast
Mix well.
-500g wheat flour 
-10g salt
Stir until a sticky dough forms.
Cover and let it rest for 3h.
Slightly wet your hands and stretch and fold all 4 edges of the dough. 
Cover and let it rest for 30mins.
Repeat 4x in total.
Preheat the oven to 250C.
Put the dough on a floured working surface and shape into a loaf.
Place in a ovenproof baking dish with parchment paper.
Cover and bake for 30mins.
Remove the lid, lower the temperature to 220C and bake for another 20mins.
Let it cool down completely and enjoy!
-
Das EINFACHSTE Brot üçû

Ich liebe ein gutes, knuspriges Brot und ich verspreche euch: Dieses Brot ist 100 % idiotensicher! ü´∂
REZEPT (1 Laib, 6 Stunden Zubereitungszeit):
- 350 ml Wasser, Zimmertemperatur
- 8 g frische Hefe oder 3 g Trockenhefe
Gut verr√ºhren.
- 500 g Weizenmehl
- 10 g Salz
Zu einem klebrigen Teig verr√ºhren.
Abgedeckt 3 Stunden ruhen lassen.
Die H√§nde leicht anfeuchten und jede Ecke lang ziehen und √ºber den Teig falten.
Abgedeckt 30 Minuten ruhen lassen.
Insgesamt 4-mal wiederholen.
Den Backofen auf 250 ¬∞C Ober-Unterhitze vorheizen.
Den Teig auf eine bemehlte Arbeitsfl√§che geben und zu einem Laib formen.
In eine ofenfeste Auflaufform mit Backpapier legen.
Abgedeckt 30 Minuten backen.
Deckel abnehmen, Temperatur auf 220 ¬∞C reduzieren und weitere 20 Minuten backen.
Vollst√§ndig abk√ºhlen lassen und genie√üen!

VLOG - Mein Sohn ist 4 geworden & ich glaube es war auf jeden Fall ein Geburtstag ‚Äûto remember" - & was mir dieser Geburtstag wieder gezeigt hat war, dass Kinder sich nicht an jedes Spielzeug erinnern, aber an Erlebnisse.
Geschenke m√ºssen nicht teuer sein - aber sie k√∂nnen unbezahlbar werden.
Wenn wir Kindern Erlebnisse schenken, schenken wir mehr als einen sch√∂nen Tag:
Wir geben ihnen das Gef√ºhl, gesehen und geh√∂rt zu werden.

Wir zeigen, dass N√§he, Aufmerksamkeit und gemeinsame Zeit wichtiger sind als Dinge.
Wir leben ihnen Werte vor & das ver√§ndert nicht nur die Beziehung zwischen uns und dem Kind sondern pr√§gt auch, wie sie sp√§ter mit anderen Menschen umgehen
Wie sie schenken. Wie sie lieben. Wie sie leben.

Pizza Sandwich ü§§üî•
‚†Ä
I finally tried the viral pizza sandwich and I absolutely loved it! Next time you‚Äôre making pizza, try this simple trick to turn your pizza dough into the best sandwiches!
‚†Ä
RECIPE (4-6 pizzas)
For the pizza dough:
- 400 g all purpose flour
- 200 g poolish (preferment)
- 250 g water
- 5 g dry yeast
- 10 g salt
‚†Ä
Poolish:
- 100 g flour
- 100 g water
- small pinch yeast
‚†Ä
Toppings (use whatever you like):
- olive oil
- vegan pesto
- vegan ricotta (optional)
- arugula
- sun-dried tomatoes (optional)
- vegan chicken (or tofu)
‚†Ä
‚ù∂ Prepare the poolish at least 8 hours before mixing the dough. (If you don‚Äôt want to plan ahead you can skip the preferment!)
‚ù∑ Mix all ingredients for the pizza dough until you have a shaggy dough. Let it rest for 15 minutes.
‚ù∏ Stretch & fold the dough to create dough strength. Repeat until you have a strong and smooth dough.
‚ùπ Ferment at room temperature until you have a gassy dough that has at least doubled in size.
‚ù∫ Divide the dough into pieces, shape each piece into a tight ball, then cover and let it rest at room temperature for 1-3 hours or in the fridge for up to 24 hours.
‚ùª Cover in semolina or flour, then shape into a pizza, leaving only a thin crust.
‚ùº Drizzle with olive oil, then fold in half.
‚ùΩ Bake at 250¬∞C until golden brown.
‚ùæ Top with your favorite toppings and enjoy one of the best sandwiches of your life! ü§§
‚†Ä
Please tag me¬†if you make it, I love seeing your remakes! <3
‚†Ä

Sauerkraut ü•¨ an easy introduction to fermentation!
‚†Ä
Sauerkraut is the perfect example of classic lactic acid fermentation. Fermentation preserves the cabbage, making it sour and flavourful and full of good bacteria for the gut. Fermenting is easier than you might think, you should give it a try!
‚†Ä
RECIPE
- 1 head of white cabbage (or red cabbage)
- 2% salt (1 kg cabbage = 20 g salt)
‚†Ä
Spices (optional):
- Juniper berries
- Bay leaves
- caraway seeds
- pepper
‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚ù∂ Remove a few outer leaves. These will serve as a cover later.
‚ù∑ Cut the cabbage into quarters, remove the stalk and slice into thin strips.
‚ù∏ Weigh the cabbage and add 2% of the weight in salt.
‚ùπ Knead/massage the cabbage with your hands for a few minutes and then leave to stand for 15 minutes.
‚ù∫ Add spices to taste. (optional)
‚ùª Place everything in a clean container and press firmly so that the cabbage is covered with water. Cover with the cabbage leaves and place a weight on top so that everything remains covered with water. 
‚ùº Leave to ferment at room temperature for 4-14 days until the desired acidity is reached. Squeeze out the air from time to time so that everything remains covered with water.

text:
Savory Cake  
Everything you need:  
1 small broccoli  
1 large carrot  
Optional: 100 g cooked ham or turkey breast  
4-5 eggs  
100 g feta cheese  
100 g grated Gouda  
Salt and pepper  

Grate the broccoli florets. Then grate the carrot as well. Cut the ham into cubes and add it to the vegetables. Crumble the feta cheese into the mixture and add the eggs. Season with salt and pepper and mix everything well. Spread the mixture on a baking sheet or place it in a baking dish lined with parchment paper, about a thumb's width thick. Sprinkle with Gouda cheese and bake in the preheated oven at 200 degrees Celsius (fan) for about 25 minutes. Baking time may vary depending on the oven. Enjoy!

text:
4-hour cooking session, 30-minute break. #dinner #steak #truffle

1st course: 
The main course is a 3-hour slow-cooked wagyu sirloin served with blue cheese foam, black truffle, onion rings, and a classic veal reduction stock. 

Notes:
The aim was to create a refined gourmet snack served as dinner. The combinations worked wonderfully, that fatty piece of wagyu with a cheese blue chees sauce and crunchy onion rings ‚Äì chefs kiss!

Taste 8/10
Visuals 8/10
Criticism: Could have been more refined, sauce a touch foamier.

2nd course: 
Blueberry cheesecake served with creme brule ricotta lemon cake, lemon yoghurt ice cream, blueberry sauce, oat honey crumble, soft vanilla blueberry sauce, and cheesecake whipped cream. 

Notes: 
Had nothing in particular in mind here. Taste-wise, texture, and visuals I was incredibly satisfied. It was just one of those dishes you taste, and you have this nice light bulb moment of "wow".

Taste 9.5/10
Visual 7.5/10 
Criticism: A touch better portion balance.

text:
Not long ago, I was invited to a creator event in LA with other food content creators‚Äîan incredible experience where we all got to cook together. I decided to make one of my favourite desserts, set big expectations for myself‚Ä¶ and then completely flopped. FML.

Everything was smooth sailing, but I had doubts about the gelatine available there (probably should have added more but didn‚Äôt). Then, when the final mascarpone cream mixture was ready to be whipped‚Äîit just wasn't holding structure. Different country, different gelatin strength? Maybe just a poor excuse. You tell me!

While the flavour wasn‚Äôt the issue here, I had a golden chance to switch up the plating and save it with a clever touch, but my insecurity kicked in, and I doubled down on the original setup (first pictured), knowing full well in the back of mind that it wouldn‚Äôt work. Maybe it was also the pressure of 20 people silently watching, or maybe I just fumbled‚Äîeither way, it‚Äôs something to work on.

I guess, no matter how many times you‚Äôve made something, there are always curveballs. You just have to know how to catch them. More than anything, it reminded me how important it is to adapt in the moment‚Äîsomething I‚Äôll keep in mind as I move toward opening a business.

text:
‚û°Ô∏è Paar WhatsApp Nachrichten beantworten, bisschen auf IG und Tiktok schauen, was es Neues gibt und 1-2 Mal am Tag die privaten Mails checken. Danach bin ich ‚Äûoff‚Äú ‚Äì wie fr√ºher. Das ist passiert seit ich das konsequent durchziehe: 

‚úÖ Ich brauche kein ‚ÄûDigital Detox‚Äú mehr, wo ich alle Apps l√∂sche und deaktiviere, weil ich einen gesunden konstanten Umgang pflege, statt eine toxische und intensive on/off-Beziehungen mit Social Media.

‚úÖ Meine Zeit geh√∂rt mir, die Apps stehlen sie mir nicht durch ‚ÄûDoomscrollen‚Äú und Kontrollverlust.

‚úÖ Ich bin wieder kreativ und lade selbst mehr Content hoch, statt Konsumentin zu sein. 

‚úÖ Meine Augen erholen sich besser durch weniger Bildschirmzeit, sind nicht mehr so trocken. Bin keine Brillentr√§gerin, m√∂chte auch dass es so lang wie m√∂glich so bleibt. 

‚úÖ Ich lese mehr B√ºcher und kann wieder mehr qualitatives Wissen langfristig aufnehmen, statt schnelle Informationshappen, die nicht h√§ngenbleiben. 

‚úÖ Die Gespr√§che mit Freunden sind inhaltvoller geworden.

‚úÖ Mein E-Mail Postfach ist immer aufger√§umt, ich erledige alles direkt statt zu prokrastinieren und auf Social Media rumzuh√§ngen ‚Äì habe mehr Zeit als vorher zur Verf√ºgung.

‚ú®üó£Ô∏è Kanns nur empfehlen, probiert‚Äòs mal aus. Geht wie fr√ºher ‚Äûoffline‚Äú bzw. immer wieder mal ‚Äûonline‚Äú statt auf default Daueronline zu sein. Einfach Mobile Daten aus, Handy weg und nach paar Stunden wieder aktivieren.

1.‚ÄØWeniger ist oft mehr ‚Äì vor allem beim Teint.
Anfangs denkt man oft: ‚ÄûJe mehr Foundation, desto makelloser.‚Äú Aber zu viel Produkt betont eher Poren und Texturen. Eine d√ºnne, gut verblendete Schicht, eventuell nur punktuell mit Concealer erg√§nzt, sieht nat√ºrlicher aus und h√§lt besser.

2.‚ÄØHautpflege ist das eigentliche Make-up.
Make-up sitzt nur so gut wie die Haut darunter. Eine gepflegte, gut durchfeuchtete Haut macht den gr√∂√üten Unterschied ‚Äì egal ob bei Drogerie- oder High-End-Produkten. Ohne gute Base bringt der beste Highlighter nichts.

3.‚ÄØFarben und Texturen sind nicht ‚Äûfalsch‚Äú ‚Äì du brauchst nur die richtige Technik.
Ein knalliges Rouge oder ein k√ºhler Lippenstift wirkt schnell ‚Äûtoo much‚Äú, wenn man nicht wei√ü, wie man es ausbalanciert. Aber mit etwas √úbung wird genau das zum Signature Look. Es geht weniger um ‚ÄûWas darf ich tragen?‚Äú ‚Äì und mehr um ‚ÄûWie setze ich es ein?‚Äú.
